          "body": "At 3:16 Qohelet pivots from the doctrine of time to its hardest test case: the courts. *In the place of justice there is wickedness, and in the place of righteousness there is wickedness.* The institutions that should embody *mishpat* are corrupted. Qohelet's answer (3:17) is not reform but eschatology: *God will judge both the righteous and the wicked, for a time for every matter and for every deed is there.* The same *et* (appointed time) that governs birth and death (3:2) also governs judgment (3:17). The God who made everything beautiful in its time has set a time when every wrong will be addressed. The NT explicitly takes up this expectation in Acts 17:31 (God *has fixed a day* on which He will judge the world) and 2 Corinthians 5:10 (we must all appear before the judgment seat of Christ)."
